            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is molar mass?</h2>
              <p>
                Molar mass is the mass of one mole of a substance. It is usually
                expressed in grams per mole (g/mol). One mole contains
                Avogadro’s number of particles, approximately \(6.022 \times
                10^{23}\) entities (atoms, molecules, ions, etc.).
              </p>
              <p>
                For an element, the molar mass is numerically equal to its
                relative atomic mass on the periodic table (e.g., carbon ≈ 12.01
                g/mol). For a compound, the molar mass is the sum of the molar
                masses of all atoms in its chemical formula.
              </p>

              <h2>Formula for molar mass of a compound</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose a compound has the chemical formula \(
                \mathrm{A}_{a}\mathrm{B}_{b}\mathrm{C}_{c}\ldots \), where \(a,
                b, c, \ldots\) are the number of atoms of each element in one
                formula unit.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mono">
                  \( M = a \cdot M_\mathrm{A} + b \cdot M_\mathrm{B} + c \cdot
                  M_\mathrm{C} + \dots \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  where \(M\) is the molar mass of the compound, and
                  \(M_\mathrm{A}, M_\mathrm{B}, M_\mathrm{C}, \dots\) are the
                  molar masses of each element (from the periodic table).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: molar mass of water (H₂O)</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Identify elements and counts: H: 2 atoms, O: 1 atom.</li>
                <li>
                  Look up atomic (molar) masses: H ≈ 1.008 g/mol, O ≈ 15.999
                  g/mol.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Multiply and sum:
                  <div class="formula-box mono">
                    \( M(\mathrm{H_2O}) = 2 \times 1.008 + 1 \times 15.999
                    \approx 18.015 \,\text{g/mol} \)
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>How to use the molar mass calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Type a valid chemical formula into the input box (e.g.,
                  <span class="mono">C6H12O6</span>).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Include parentheses for groups, e.g.,
                  <span class="mono">(NH4)2SO4</span>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For hydrates, use “·” or a dot, e.g.,
                  <span class="mono">CuSO4·5H2O</span> or
                  <span class="mono">CuSO4.5H2O</span>.
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>Calculate molar mass</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Read the total molar mass and the detailed element breakdown
                  table.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Molar mass vs. molecular mass</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Molar mass</strong> is the mass of one mole of
                  entities, in g/mol.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Molecular mass</strong> (or molecular weight) is the
                  mass of a single molecule, usually in atomic mass units (u or
                  Da).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Numerically, they are often very similar (e.g., water: ≈ 18.015
                u per molecule and ≈ 18.015 g/mol per mole), but the units and
                physical meaning differ.
              </p>

              <h2>Common molar masses (for quick reference)</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Water, H₂O: ≈ 18.015 g/mol</li>
                <li>Glucose, C₆H₁₂O₆: ≈ 180.16 g/mol</li>
                <li>Sodium chloride, NaCl: ≈ 58.44 g/mol</li>
                <li>Carbon dioxide, CO₂: ≈ 44.01 g/mol</li>
                <li>Ammonia, NH₃: ≈ 17.03 g/mol</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What formulas can I enter?</h3>
              <p>
                You can enter most inorganic and organic formulas using element
                symbols, integers, parentheses, and hydrate dots. Examples:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><span class="mono">Fe2O3</span></li>
                <li><span class="mono">Al2(SO4)3</span></li>
                <li><span class="mono">CH3COOH</span> (acetic acid)</li>
                <li>
                  <span class="mono">K4[Fe(CN)6]</span> (coordination compound)
                </li>
                <li><span class="mono">MgSO4·7H2O</span> (Epsom salt)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Where do the atomic masses come from?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator uses standard atomic weights from IUPAC (rounded
                to a reasonable number of significant figures for typical
                laboratory calculations). For most educational and practical
                purposes, this precision is more than sufficient.
              </p>

              <h3>Why is my manual result slightly different?</h3>
              <p>
                Small differences (in the third or fourth decimal place) usually
                come from rounding atomic masses to different numbers of
                significant figures. If you need very high precision, make sure
                you use the same atomic weights and rounding rules consistently.
              </p>

              <h3>How is molar mass used in stoichiometry?</h3>
              <p>Molar mass is the conversion factor between mass and moles:</p>
              <div class="formula-box mono">\[ n = \frac{m}{M} \]</div>
              <p>
                where \(n\) is the amount of substance in moles, \(m\) is the
                mass in grams, and \(M\) is the molar mass in g/mol. This
                relationship is central to stoichiometric calculations such as
                reactant requirements and theoretical yields.
              </p>
